points.description:
Define the essential payment operations with each approach:
```java
// Interface approach - defines a contract
public interface PaymentMethod {
    boolean processPayment(double amount);
    boolean refundPayment(String transactionId, double amount);
    TransactionStatus checkStatus(String transactionId);
    String getPaymentMethodName();
}

// Abstract class approach - provides partial implementation
public abstract class PaymentMethod {
    protected String merchantId;
    protected Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(getClass());

    // Common utility method
    protected final String generateTransactionId() {
        return UUID.randomUUID().toString();
    }

    // Abstract methods to be implemented
    public abstract boolean processPayment(double amount);
    public abstract boolean refundPayment(String transactionId, double amount);
    public abstract TransactionStatus checkStatus(String transactionId);
}
```

Interface approach offers more flexibility for implementing classes:
```java
// With interfaces, a class can implement multiple behaviors
public class PayPalPayment implements PaymentMethod, ThirdPartyAuthentication {
    // Implements PaymentMethod
    @Override
    public boolean processPayment(double amount) {
        // PayPal-specific processing
        return payPalClient.makePayment(amount);
    }

    // Also implements ThirdPartyAuthentication
    @Override
    public void authenticate(Credentials credentials) {
        payPalClient.login(credentials);
    }

    // Other method implementations...
}

// With abstract class, limited to single inheritance
public class CreditCardPayment extends PaymentMethod {
    // Can't also extend PaymentGateway or another class
    @Override
    public boolean processPayment(double amount) {
        // Credit card processing
        return processor.charge(cardNumber, amount);
    }

    // Other method implementations...
}
```

Abstract classes can provide shared code for subclasses:
```java
// Abstract class with shared implementation
public abstract class PaymentMethod {
    // Shared state
    protected TransactionRepository transactionRepo = new TransactionRepository();

    // Template method pattern
    public final boolean processPayment(double amount) {
        // Common pre-processing
        String transactionId = generateTransactionId();
        logAttempt(transactionId, amount);

        // Specific payment processing by subclasses
        boolean success = doProcessPayment(transactionId, amount);

        // Common post-processing
        logResult(transactionId, success);
        notifyResult(success, amount);

        return success;
    }

    // Subclasses implement this
    protected abstract boolean doProcessPayment(String transactionId, double amount);

    // Shared utility methods
    private void logAttempt(String id, double amount) {
        transactionRepo.logAttempt(id, amount);
    }
}

// Interfaces can't provide implementation before Java 8
// With Java 8+, interfaces can have default methods
public interface PaymentMethod {
    boolean processPayment(double amount);

    // Default method implementation
    default String formatAmount(double amount) {
        return String.format("$%.2f", amount);
    }
}
```

Both can provide default behaviors, but with different approaches:
```java
// Interface with default methods (Java 8+)
public interface PaymentMethod {
    boolean processPayment(double amount);

    // Default implementation
    default boolean supportsRefunds() {
        return false; // Most payments support refunds, but not all
    }

    default TransactionStatus checkStatus(String transactionId) {
        return TransactionStatus.UNKNOWN; // Default behavior
    }
}

// Abstract class with concrete and abstract methods
public abstract class PaymentMethod {
    // Concrete method with implementation
    public boolean supportsRefunds() {
        return false; // Default behavior
    }

    // Abstract method forcing implementation
    public abstract boolean processPayment(double amount);

    // Non-abstract method that can be overridden
    public TransactionStatus checkStatus(String transactionId) {
        return TransactionStatus.UNKNOWN; // Default implementation
    }
}
```

Abstract classes can maintain state, interfaces typically can't:
```java
// Abstract class with state
public abstract class PaymentMethod {
    protected String merchantId;
    protected boolean testMode;
    protected List<Transaction> transactions = new ArrayList<>();

    public PaymentMethod(String merchantId, boolean testMode) {
        this.merchantId = merchantId;
        this.testMode = testMode;
    }

    public List<Transaction> getTransactions() {
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(transactions);
    }
}

// Interface approach requires each implementation to manage state
public interface PaymentMethod {
    boolean processPayment(double amount);
    List<Transaction> getTransactionHistory();
}

public class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentMethod {
    private String merchantId; // Each implementation manages own state
    private List<Transaction> transactions = new ArrayList<>();

    // Implementation-specific state
    private CreditCardProcessor processor;
    private String encryptedCardNumber;
}
```

Abstract classes offer more access control options:
```java
// Abstract class with various access modifiers
public abstract class PaymentMethod {
    // Available to all
    public final String getMerchantName() {
        return merchantName;
    }

    // Available to subclasses only
    protected void logTransaction(String transactionId) {
        // Implementation...
    }

    // Available to subclasses in same package
    void validateMerchantAccount() {
        // Implementation...
    }

    // Private - not available to subclasses
    private String encryptData(String data) {
        // Implementation...
    }
}

// Interface methods are all public (before Java 9)
public interface PaymentMethod {
    // Implicitly public
    boolean processPayment(double amount);

    // Explicitly public (same as above)
    public boolean refundPayment(String transactionId, double amount);

    // Java 9+ allows private methods
    private String encryptData(String data) { // Java 9+ only
        // Implementation...
    }
}
```

Interfaces can evolve more easily without breaking implementations:
```java
// Original interface
public interface PaymentMethod {
    boolean processPayment(double amount);
}

// Later version - add method with default implementation
public interface PaymentMethod {
    boolean processPayment(double amount);

    // New method with default - existing implementations still work
    default boolean processRecurringPayment(double amount, int intervalDays) {
        // Default implementation just calls regular payment
        return processPayment(amount);
    }
}

// With abstract class, adding new abstract method breaks existing code
public abstract class PaymentMethod {
    public abstract boolean processPayment(double amount);

    // Adding this would break all existing subclasses
    public abstract boolean processRecurringPayment(double amount, int intervalDays);
}

// Must add concrete method instead
public abstract class PaymentMethod {
    public abstract boolean processPayment(double amount);

    // Non-abstract method won't break existing code
    public boolean processRecurringPayment(double amount, int intervalDays) {
        return processPayment(amount);
    }
}
```

Interface-based designs are often easier to test:
```java
// Interface-based design - easy to mock
public interface PaymentProcessor {
    PaymentResult process(PaymentRequest request);
}

// Test with a mock
@Test
public void testOrderPayment() {
    // Easy to create test double
    PaymentProcessor mockProcessor = mock(PaymentProcessor.class);
    when(mockProcessor.process(any())).thenReturn(new PaymentResult(true));

    OrderService service = new OrderService(mockProcessor);
    Order order = new Order(100.0);

    boolean result = service.payForOrder(order);
    assertTrue(result);
}

// Abstract class - harder to test
public abstract class PaymentProcessor {
    // Tied to implementation; harder to mock
    protected final TransactionLog transactionLog = new TransactionLog();

    public final PaymentResult process(PaymentRequest request) {
        // Implementation with side effects
    }

    protected abstract boolean doProcess(PaymentRequest request);
}
```

For complex payment systems, consider a hybrid approach:
```java
// Core interface defines the contract
public interface PaymentMethod {
    PaymentResult processPayment(PaymentRequest request);
    RefundResult refundPayment(RefundRequest request);
    TransactionStatus checkStatus(String transactionId);
}

// Abstract base class implements the interface with common functionality
public abstract class BasePaymentProcessor implements PaymentMethod {
    protected final PaymentConfig config;
    protected final TransactionLog log;

    public BasePaymentProcessor(PaymentConfig config) {
        this.config = config;
        this.log = new TransactionLog(config.getMerchantId());
    }

    // Template method pattern
    @Override
    public final PaymentResult processPayment(PaymentRequest request) {
        log.logAttempt(request);
        validateRequest(request);

        PaymentResult result = doProcessPayment(request);

        log.logResult(result);
        notifyPaymentComplete(result);

        return result;
    }

    // Subclasses implement this
    protected abstract PaymentResult doProcessPayment(PaymentRequest request);
}

// Additional capability interfaces
public interface SubscriptionCapable {
    SubscriptionResult createSubscription(SubscriptionRequest request);
}

// Concrete implementation using both
public class CreditCardProcessor extends BasePaymentProcessor 
    implements SubscriptionCapable {

    @Override
    protected PaymentResult doProcessPayment(PaymentRequest request) {
        // Credit card specific implementation
    }

    @Override
    public SubscriptionResult createSubscription(SubscriptionRequest request) {
        // Subscription implementation
    }
}
```

Use interfaces with adapters for external payment integrations:
```java
// Common interface for all payment providers
public interface PaymentProvider {
    TransactionResult processPayment(PaymentDetails details, double amount);
    TransactionResult refundPayment(String transactionId, double amount);
}

// Adapter for Stripe API
public class StripeAdapter implements PaymentProvider {
    private final StripeClient client;

    @Override
    public TransactionResult processPayment(PaymentDetails details, double amount) {
        // Convert to Stripe's format
        StripePaymentIntent intent = client.createPaymentIntent(
            convertToStripeFormat(details),
            Math.round(amount * 100) // Convert to cents
        );

        return mapStripeResponse(intent);
    }

    @Override
    public TransactionResult refundPayment(String transactionId, double amount) {
        StripeRefund refund = client.refundPayment(
            transactionId,
            Math.round(amount * 100) // Convert to cents
        );

        return mapStripeRefundResponse(refund);
    }
}

// Adapter for PayPal API
public class PayPalAdapter implements PaymentProvider {
    private final PayPalAPI paypal;

    @Override
    public TransactionResult processPayment(PaymentDetails details, double amount) {
        // Convert to PayPal's format and API
        PayPalPaymentRequest request = convertToPayPalFormat(details, amount);
        PayPalResult result = paypal.makePayment(request);

        return mapPayPalResult(result);
    }
}
```

Use interfaces to represent optional payment capabilities:
```java
// Core payment functionality interface
public interface PaymentMethod {
    TransactionResult processPayment(PaymentRequest request);
}

// Additional optional capabilities as separate interfaces
public interface SupportsRefunds {
    RefundResult refundPayment(String transactionId, double amount);
}

public interface SupportsRecurringPayments {
    SubscriptionResult setupRecurringPayment(RecurringPaymentRequest request);
    boolean cancelRecurringPayment(String subscriptionId);
}

public interface SupportsTokenization {
    String tokenizePaymentMethod(PaymentMethodDetails details);
    TransactionResult chargeWithToken(String token, double amount);
}

// Each payment method implements the capabilities it supports
public class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentMethod, 
                                      SupportsRefunds, 
                                      SupportsTokenization {
    // Implementation of all supported capabilities
}

public class PayPalPayment implements PaymentMethod, 
                                   SupportsRefunds, 
                                   SupportsRecurringPayments {
    // Implementation of all supported capabilities
}

// Client code checks for capabilities before using them
public void processRefund(PaymentMethod method, String transactionId, double amount) {
    if (method instanceof SupportsRefunds) {
        SupportsRefunds refundable = (SupportsRefunds) method;
        refundable.refundPayment(transactionId, amount);
    } else {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Payment method doesn't support refunds");
    }
}
```

**Default methods** are methods defined in an interface with the `default` keyword that provide a concrete implementation. They allow interfaces to evolve without breaking existing implementations: 
```java
public interface MyInterface {
    void abstractMethod(); // Regular abstract method

    default void defaultMethod() {
        System.out.println("Default implementation");
    }
}
```

When a class implements multiple interfaces with the same default method, the **diamond problem** arises. Java resolves this by requiring the implementing class to override the conflicting method: 
```java
public interface A { default void method() { /* impl A */ } }
public interface B { default void method() { /* impl B */ } }

public class C implements A, B {
    @Override
    public void method() {
        A.super.method(); // Choose implementation from A
        // Or B.super.method(); // Or from B
        // Or custom implementation
    }
}
```

Default methods enable new design patterns, such as the **Trait pattern**, where interfaces with default methods act like **traits** (reusable chunks of behavior) that can be mixed into classes without inheritance: 
```java
public interface Loggable {
    default Logger getLogger() {
        return LoggerFactory.getLogger(getClass());
    }

    default void logInfo(String message) {
        getLogger().info(message);
    }
}

// Any class can now become loggable
public class MyService implements Loggable {
    public void process() {
        logInfo("Processing started"); // Uses the trait method
        // ...
    }
}
```

Since Java 9, interfaces can also have **private methods** (both instance and static), which enable code reuse within the interface itself: 
```java
public interface Validator {
    default boolean validateWithLogging(String input) {
        log("Validating: " + input);
        return validate(input);
    }

    default boolean validate(String input) {
        return !isNullOrEmpty(input);
    }

    private boolean isNullOrEmpty(String text) { // Helper method
        return text == null || text.isEmpty();
    }

    private static void log(String message) { // Private static helper
        System.out.println(message);
    }
}
```

A **functional interface** is an interface that has exactly one abstract method (SAM - Single Abstract Method). It can be annotated with `@FunctionalInterface`, though this is optional: 
```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Runnable {
    void run();
}
```

Functional interfaces enable **lambda expressions**, which provide a concise way to represent an anonymous function that can be passed around: 
```java
// Traditional anonymous class
Runnable runnable1 = new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
};

// Lambda expression
Runnable runnable2 = () -> System.out.println("Hello");
```

**Method references** provide a shorthand syntax for lambda expressions that call a single existing method: 
```java
// Lambda expression
Function<String, Integer> strLength = s -> s.length();

// Method reference equivalent
Function<String, Integer> strLength = String::length;
```
There are four types of method references:
1. Reference to a static method: `ClassName::staticMethod`
2. Reference to an instance method of a particular object: `object::instanceMethod`
3. Reference to an instance method of an arbitrary object of a particular type: `ClassName::instanceMethod`
4. Reference to a constructor: `ClassName::new`

Many functional interfaces provide default methods for combining functions: 
```java
// Combining Predicates
Predicate<String> isNotEmpty = s -> !s.isEmpty();
Predicate<String> isNotTooLong = s -> s.length() <= 10;
Predicate<String> isValid = isNotEmpty.and(isNotTooLong);

// Chaining Functions
Function<String, String> trim = String::trim;
Function<String, String> toUpperCase = String::toUpperCase;
Function<String, String> trimAndUpperCase = trim.andThen(toUpperCase);
```

The Java compiler can often infer the types in lambda expressions from the context, making code more concise: 
```java
// Explicit parameter types
Comparator<String> comp = (String s1, String s2) -> s1.length() - s2.length();

// Inferred parameter types
Comparator<String> comp = (s1, s2) -> s1.length() - s2.length();
```

While the standard library covers many common cases, you can create custom functional interfaces for specific needs: 
```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface TriFunction<T, U, V, R> {
    R apply(T t, U u, V v);

    default <S> TriFunction<T, U, V, S> andThen(Function<? super R, ? extends S> after) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(after);
        return (T t, U u, V v) -> after.apply(apply(t, u, v));
    }
}
```

Lambda expressions can access variables from their enclosing scope if they are final or effectively final (not modified after initialization): 
```java
String prefix = "User: ";

// Works because prefix is effectively final
Function<String, String> addPrefix = name -> prefix + name;

// Would cause compilation error if you tried to modify prefix after this:
// prefix = "Customer: ";
```

```java
// Traditional approach with anonymous class
Collections.sort(products, new Comparator<Product>() {
    @Override
    public int compare(Product p1, Product p2) {
        return Double.compare(p1.getPrice(), p2.getPrice());
    }
});

// With lambda expression - much more concise
products.sort((p1, p2) -> Double.compare(p1.getPrice(), p2.getPrice()));

// Using method reference - even cleaner
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice));
```

```java
// Traditional approach for multiple criteria
Collections.sort(products, new Comparator<Product>() {
    @Override
    public int compare(Product p1, Product p2) {
        // First compare by category
        int result = p1.getCategory().compareTo(p2.getCategory());
        if (result != 0) return result;

        // Then by price
        return Double.compare(p1.getPrice(), p2.getPrice());
    }
});

// With lambda and method chaining - more readable
products.sort(
    Comparator.comparing(Product::getCategory)
             .thenComparing(Product::getPrice)
);

// Add more criteria easily
products.sort(
    Comparator.comparing(Product::getCategory)
             .thenComparing(Product::getPrice)
             .thenComparing(Product::getRating, Comparator.reverseOrder())
);
```

```java
// Custom ordering with lambdas

// Sort by price per unit (best value first)
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(
    product -> product.getPrice() / product.getUnitQuantity()
));

// Sort by discount percentage (highest discount first)
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(
    product -> {
        double regularPrice = product.getRegularPrice();
        double salePrice = product.getSalePrice();
        return regularPrice > 0 ? (regularPrice - salePrice) / regularPrice : 0;
    },
    Comparator.reverseOrder() // Highest discount first
));

// Seasonal products first, then by price
boolean isHolidaySeason = Calendar.getInstance().get(Calendar.MONTH) == Calendar.DECEMBER;
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(
    product -> !product.isSeasonalProduct(isHolidaySeason) // Negated for sorting
).thenComparing(
    Product::getPrice
));
```

```java
// Handling nulls and special cases

// Traditional way with null checks
Collections.sort(products, new Comparator<Product>() {
    @Override
    public int compare(Product p1, Product p2) {
        // Handle potentially null values
        if (p1.getReleaseDate() == null && p2.getReleaseDate() == null) {
            return 0;
        } else if (p1.getReleaseDate() == null) {
            return 1; // Nulls last
        } else if (p2.getReleaseDate() == null) {
            return -1; // Nulls last
        }
        return p1.getReleaseDate().compareTo(p2.getReleaseDate());
    }
});

// With lambda and built-in null handling
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(
    Product::getReleaseDate,
    Comparator.nullsLast(Comparator.naturalOrder())
));

// Special case: featured products first, then normal sorting
products.sort(
    Comparator.comparing(Product::isFeatured, Comparator.reverseOrder())
             .thenComparing(Product::getCategory)
             .thenComparing(Product::getPrice)
);
```

```java
// Traditional approach to dynamic sorting
public Comparator<Product> getSortComparator(SortType sortType) {
    switch (sortType) {
        case PRICE_LOW_TO_HIGH:
            return new Comparator<Product>() {
                @Override
                public int compare(Product p1, Product p2) {
                    return Double.compare(p1.getPrice(), p2.getPrice());
                }
            };
        case PRICE_HIGH_TO_LOW:
            return new Comparator<Product>() {
                @Override
                public int compare(Product p1, Product p2) {
                    return Double.compare(p2.getPrice(), p1.getPrice());
                }
            };
        // Other cases...
    }
}

// With lambdas - much cleaner
public Comparator<Product> getSortComparator(SortType sortType) {
    return switch (sortType) {
        case PRICE_LOW_TO_HIGH -> Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice);
        case PRICE_HIGH_TO_LOW -> Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice).reversed();
        case BY_NAME -> Comparator.comparing(Product::getName);
        case TOP_RATED -> Comparator.comparing(Product::getRating).reversed();
        case NEWEST -> Comparator.comparing(Product::getReleaseDate,
                                  Comparator.nullsLast(Comparator.reverseOrder()));
    };
}

// Simplifies usage
products.sort(getSortComparator(userSelectedSortType));
```

```java
// Traditional approach: separate filtering and sorting
List<Product> filtered = new ArrayList<>();
for (Product p : products) {
    if (p.getCategory().equals(selectedCategory) && p.getPrice() <= maxPrice) {
        filtered.add(p);
    }
}
Collections.sort(filtered, priceComparator);

// With Stream API and lambdas: combined in one operation
List<Product> filteredAndSorted = products.stream()
    .filter(p -> p.getCategory().equals(selectedCategory))
    .filter(p -> p.getPrice() <= maxPrice)
    .sorted(Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice))
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

// Get just top 5 products after filtering and sorting
List<Product> topFiveAffordable = products.stream()
    .filter(p -> p.getCategory().equals(selectedCategory))
    .filter(p -> p.getPrice() <= maxPrice)
    .sorted(Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice))
    .limit(5)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

```java
// Complex business rules are easy to implement with lambdas

// Weighted rank based on multiple factors
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(product -> {
    double score = 0.0;

    // Sales velocity factor (30% weight)
    score += 0.3 * (product.getSales() / (product.getDaysSinceLaunch() + 1));

    // Profit margin factor (25% weight)
    score += 0.25 * ((product.getPrice() - product.getCost()) / product.getPrice());

    // Rating factor (25% weight)
    score += 0.25 * product.getAverageRating();

    // Stock level factor (20% weight) - lower stock gets priority
    score += 0.2 * (100 - Math.min(product.getStockLevel(), 100)) / 100.0;

    return -score;  // Negative for descending order
}));

// Sort based on user's purchase history
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(product -> {
    // Check if user previously purchased products from this category
    boolean purchasedCategory = userHistory.hasPurchasedCategory(product.getCategory());

    // Check if user viewed this product recently
    boolean recentlyViewed = userHistory.hasViewedRecently(product.getId());

    // Create a relevance score (higher is better)
    int relevanceScore = 0;
    if (purchasedCategory) relevanceScore += 2;
    if (recentlyViewed) relevanceScore += 3;

    // Combine with general popularity
    return -(relevanceScore + (product.getPopularityScore() / 100.0));
}));
```

```java
// Create reusable comparators with lambdas
public class ProductComparators {
    // By price
    public static Comparator<Product> byPrice() {
        return Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice);
    }

    public static Comparator<Product> byPriceDesc() {
        return Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice, Comparator.reverseOrder());
    }

    // By rating
    public static Comparator<Product> byRating() {
        return Comparator.comparing(Product::getRating, Comparator.reverseOrder());
    }

    // By freshness (newest first)
    public static Comparator<Product> byFreshness() {
        return Comparator.comparing(Product::getReleaseDate, 
                           Comparator.nullsLast(Comparator.reverseOrder()));
    }

    // By relevance with search term
    public static Comparator<Product> byRelevance(String searchTerm) {
        return Comparator.comparing(product -> {
            // Calculate relevance score based on matches in name/description
            return -calculateRelevance(product, searchTerm);
        });
    }

    // Complex: smart sort that combines multiple factors
    public static Comparator<Product> smartSort(UserPreferences prefs) {
        return (p1, p2) -> {
            // Calculate scores based on user preferences
            double score1 = calculateSmartScore(p1, prefs);
            double score2 = calculateSmartScore(p2, prefs);
            return Double.compare(score2, score1); // Higher score first
        };
    }
}

// Usage
products.sort(ProductComparators.byPrice());

// Compose different comparators
products.sort(
    ProductComparators.byRating()
        .thenComparing(ProductComparators.byPrice())
);
```

```java
// Parallel sorting for large catalogs

// For ArrayList - use parallelSort with lambda
if (products instanceof ArrayList) {
    Product[] array = products.toArray(new Product[0]);
    Arrays.parallelSort(array, Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice));
    // Convert back to list if needed
}

// With streams - parallel processing
List<Product> sortedProducts = products.parallelStream()
    .sorted(Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice))
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

// Custom parallel sorting for very large datasets
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newWorkStealingPool();

try {
    // Split the list into chunks for parallel processing
    int chunkSize = 1000;
    List<List<Product>> chunks = new ArrayList<>();

    for (int i = 0; i < products.size(); i += chunkSize) {
        chunks.add(products.subList(i, Math.min(products.size(), i + chunkSize)));
    }

    // Sort each chunk in parallel
    Comparator<Product> comparator = Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice);
    List<Future<List<Product>>> futures = new ArrayList<>();

    for (List<Product> chunk : chunks) {
        futures.add(executor.submit(() -> {
            chunk.sort(comparator);
            return chunk;
        }));
    }

    // Merge sorted chunks (simplified)
    List<Product> sorted = new ArrayList<>();
    for (Future<List<Product>> future : futures) {
        sorted.addAll(future.get());
    }
    sorted.sort(comparator); // Final merge sort

    return sorted;
} finally {
    executor.shutdown();
}
```

```java
// Optimizing lambda performance

// 1. Cache frequently used comparators instead of recreating
private static final Comparator<Product> PRICE_COMPARATOR = 
    Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice);

private static final Comparator<Product> RATING_COMPARATOR = 
    Comparator.comparing(Product::getRating, Comparator.reverseOrder());

// Use cached comparators
products.sort(PRICE_COMPARATOR);

// 2. Avoid capturing large objects in lambdas
public void sortProducts(List<Product> products, String searchTerm) {
    // Bad: captures 'this' which might be large
    products.sort((p1, p2) -> this.compareByRelevance(p1, p2, searchTerm));

    // Better: extract only what's needed
    final String term = searchTerm.toLowerCase(); // Capture only the search term
    products.sort((p1, p2) -> {
        int rel1 = calculateRelevance(p1.getName(), p1.getDescription(), term);
        int rel2 = calculateRelevance(p2.getName(), p2.getDescription(), term);
        return Integer.compare(rel2, rel1);
    });
}

// 3. Use primitive comparisons where possible
// Less efficient - creates Double objects for comparison
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(p -> p.getPrice()));

// More efficient - uses primitive comparison
products.sort(Comparator.comparingDouble(Product::getPrice));
```

```java
// Specialized comparators for domain-specific sorting

// Geographic proximity sorting based on user location
Location userLocation = getUserLocation();
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(product -> {
    // Calculate distance between user and product warehouse
    Location productLocation = product.getWarehouseLocation();
    return calculateDistance(userLocation, productLocation);
}));

// Time-based sorting for perishable products
LocalDate today = LocalDate.now();
products.sort(Comparator.comparing(product -> {
    if (product.isPerishable()) {
        // Sort by days until expiration (ascending)
        return ChronoUnit.DAYS.between(today, product.getExpirationDate());
    } else {
        // Non-perishable products go last
        return Long.MAX_VALUE;
    }
}));

// Semantic comparison for natural language search results
String query = "comfortable running shoes";
